const ABOUT_BIO = [
  `I didn't take the usual path into design. I studied political science, ended up selling software training solutions, and then took an HTML and CSS class. Something clicked. Shortly after, the iPhone came out, and that changed the direction entirely.`,
  `I spent the next five years building iPhone apps. Somewhere in there I realized I cared more about how people used the app than how it was built. The code was interesting. The experience was more interesting. That's when I made the move to product design.`,
  `Having a development background made me a better designer from the start. I knew what was technically straightforward and what wasn't, which meant I could have real conversations with engineers instead of handing off files and hoping for the best. I could push back when something was over-engineered and find solutions that were both solid and buildable.`,
  `That instinct has stayed. I still test designs in code, even when it's out of scope. Figma is where I figure out what something should look like. The browser is where I find out if it actually works. Interactions that look right in a prototype can feel completely wrong when you tap them for real — and I'd rather find that out than have engineering find it for me.`,
  `More recently, AI tools have changed how I work. I can explore and test multiple directions in the time it used to take to build one. The path from idea to something you can actually react to is a lot shorter now. It's made the process faster and, honestly, more interesting.`,
  `Fifteen years in, the work is still the thing that gets me going.`,
];

